      <h1>SCSS Nesting Rules</h1>


        - Don't go more than two levels deep.  Think about your site in terms of components and style according to the top level compoent.  For example, if you have a navigation component and you want to style it's links you probably want to do something like this:

        .navigation {
          .ul {
            list-style: none;
          }

          .li {
            display: inline-block;
          }

          a {
            /* link styles */

            &:hover {
              /* hover styles */
            }
          }
        }

        As opposed to:

        .navigation {
          .ul {
            list-style: none;

            .li {
              display: inline-block;
              a {
                /* link styles */

                &:hover {
                  /* hover styles */
                }
              }
            }
          }
        }

        The reason being that we're not creating styles specific to the fact that the link is within a list (li) within the site's navigation component, but rather simply because the link is within the site's navigation itself.

        If you do need the specificity, probably a better idea is to keep those specific styles within a new class as opposed to creating a deeply nested structure to define that specificity.

        Deep nesting is a code smell.  Think smaller, more modular components if you're nesting gets too deep.

